text: Human Factors Refresher 1 Human Factors Refresher Introduction It is universally agreed that 80% of manufacturing and maintenance errors involve human factors. Detection of factors that have negative implications is key to reducing events that lead to worker injuries, wasted time, loss of revenue, and accidents. For that reason, the following topics will be reviewed in this course: general/introduction to human factors, safety culture/organizational factors, human error, performance and

limitations, environment, procedures, information, tools, and practices, communication, teamwork, professionalism and integrity, and organization’s Human Factors program (which shall include lessons learned for recurring human factors training. This is specific per organization(s)). Aviation safety relies heavily on proper manufacturing and maintenance practices. When it is not done correctly, it contributes to a significant proportion of aviation accidents and incidents. Defining Human Factors

The term Human Factors has grown increasingly popular amongst the commercial aviation industry due to the realization that human error is the cause of most issues, and the result is a system or mechanical failure. There is a variety of reasons that influence people differently as we do not all have the same capabilities, strengths, weaknesses, or limitations. Human Factors is the study of all the factors that make it easier to do the work in the right way. PEAR Model There are many concepts

related to the science and practice of human factors, however from a practical standpoint it helps to have a combined view of the primary elements when considering aviation manufacturing and maintenance. The PEAR model is often used as a mnemonic device and prompts the recall of four important considerations for human factors, these are: • People who do the job; • Environment in which people work; • Actions each person performs; • Resources necessary to complete the job. People who do the job

Human Factors Refresher 2 The human factors program has to focus on employees, their physical capabilities, and the factors that affect them, and their performance. These factors are known as physical, physiological, psychological, and psychosocial. Physical factor. Conditions like physical size, age, strength, sensory limitations must be considered to ensure an individual is physically capable of performing all the tasks that make the job. Physiological factor relates to the biology that deals

with the normal functions of a person’s mind, movement, coordination, and critical thinking; these factors may include but not limited to workload, experience, knowledge, training, attitude etc. Psychological factors relate to the mental and emotional state of a person, such as nutrition, health, lifestyle, fatigue, and chemical dependency. Psychosocial factors relate to the interrelation of social factors and individual thought and behavior, an example would be a person who has conflicts with

others. Companies should make sure their employees are not overwhelmed during work hours, workstations designed with ergonomic style in mind, have robust relationship with management and opportunity for career growth. Environment in which people work There are two types of environments that employees are exposed to, these are Physical and Organizational. The physical environment includes ranges of temperature, humidity, lighting, noises, cleanliness, and workplace design. It takes a corporate

commitment to address deficiencies within the physical environment and provide resources as needed to safely and accurately perform work. The organizational environment factors are related to cooperation, communication, shared values, mutual respect, and the company culture. An excellent organizational environment is promoted with leadership, communication, and shared goals associated with safety, profitability, and other key factors. Actions each person performs Job task analysis is the

standard human factors approach to identify knowledge, skills, and attitudes necessary to properly perform each task of a job. Many of the human factors' challenges associated with work instructions, job cards, and other technical instructions Human Factors Refresher 3 is identified as the actions. A perfectly clear understanding and documentation of actions ensures instructions and checklists are correct and easy to use by employees. Resources necessary to complete the job People, and

environment dictate the resources needed to perform the tasks of a given job accurately. Resources may be tangible such as tools and manuals and less tangible such as knowledge and time to perform the job, and communication with others. Types of Errors Human Error is defined as a human action with unintended consequences. Errors are common and inherent in life, but when errors occur in aviation the results can be costly or even worse, devastating. There are two Types of Errors, which are

unintentional and intentional. The first one, Unintentional has the highest frequency and can occur due to opinion or judgement caused by poor reasoning, carelessness, or insufficient knowledge, also known as a mistake. The second type is Intentional risk, which is an act of knowingly doing something wrong even if it results in unsafe workmanship. The Dirty Dozen The Dirty Dozen refers to twelve of the most common human error preconditions, or conditions that can act as precursors to accidents

or incidents.. 1. Lack of Communication is a key human factor that results in subpar, incorrect, or faulty workmanship. Each time communication takes place, there is potential for a misunderstanding or omission. 2. Complacency can be described as a feeling of self-satisfaction accompanied by a loss of awareness of potential dangers. 3. Lack of Knowledge. All manufacturing and maintenance practices must be performed according to the manufacturer’s standards and approved data. When in doubt, a

technician with knowledge and experience should be consulted. 4. Distraction while performing a job is a common occurrence, however as technicians, you are expected to still accurately complete the work and without errors. 5. Lack of Teamwork is also a contributor to errors in aircraft manufacturing and maintenance. 6. Fatigue is a major human factor that has contributed to many errors resulting in accidents. Fatigue can be mental of physical in nature. Fatigue reduces alertness and Human

Factors Refresher 4 often reduces a person’s ability to focus and hold attention on the task being performed. The primary reason cause of fatigue is lack of sleep, stress and overworking. 7. Lack of Resources can interfere with one’s ability to complete a task because there is a lack of supply and support. Any lack of resources to safely carry out a task can cause both non-fatal and fatal accidents. 8. Pressure. Aviation requires individuals to perform in an environment with constant pressure to

do things better and faster without making mistakes and letting things fall through the cracks. 9. Lack of Assertiveness. Assertiveness is the ability to express your feelings, opinions, beliefs, and needs in a positive, productive manner and should not be confused with being aggressive. 10. Stress. Aviation manufacturing and maintenance environments can be stressful due to many factors. 11. Lack of Awareness is defined as a failure to recognize all the consequences of an action or lack of

foresight. Each time a task is completed it must be treated as if it were the first time. 12. Norms. Norms is short for “normal,” or the way things are normally done; workplace practices, that develop over time. They are unwritten rules that are followed or tolerated by most organizations. Examples of Common Errors In maintenance, there are hundreds of different ways that one might make an unintentional mistake. However, some of the common errors related to the performance of maintenance

include: • Incorrect installation of components; • Fitting of wrong parts; • Electrical wiring discrepancies; • Forgotten tools and parts; • Failure to lubricate jackscrews, etc. All of these discrepancies can be avoided if proper procedures are followed per the work instructions. Breaking the Chain of Events Roughly 20% of all accidents are caused by a machine failure, and 80% of all accidents are caused by human factors. Originally focusing on the pilot community, human factors Human Factors

Refresher 5 awareness has now spread into the training sphere of manufacturing and maintenance technicians. An in-depth review of an aviation incident reveals time and again that a series of human errors, also known as a chain of events, was allowed to build until the accident occurred. If the chain of events is broken at the technician’s level, the likelihood of the accident occurring can be drastically decreased.
